{"source_key":"sha256-b4cec238995b260ac54aae4fdce1a71d","record_index":213,"record_hash":"sha256:b71e04c39ce1d731414de0c9243abb830c67d7902f18e53ba6c6a5bcab2e4e47","timestamp":"2026-05-31T12:15:48.479Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 8f03fc\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1642\nOutput:\n# Agentlog Local-First Publishing\n\n## Intent\n\nMake `but-agentlog` private by default.\n\nCaptured agent sessions should stay local unless the user explicitly publishes\nthem. A reviewer-facing Agent Trail page should only exist for metadata the user\nhas chosen to share, or for users who have opted into sharing agentlogs by\ndefault.\n\n## Why\n\nToday capture and publish are effectively coupled. The agent hook records a\nsession, then `but-agentlog` silently runs metadata sync. That means a user who\nhas GitMeta sync configured can publish every captured agentlog without taking a\nseparate sharing action.\n\nThat is too leaky for normal work. A user may be:\n\n- exploring private customer metrics or internal stats on a public repository\n- using an agent for sensitive investigation before deciding what belongs in a PR\n- not ready to share a branch's agent context yet\n- philosophically fine with local capture but not automatic propagation\n\nThe safer default is local-first capture plus explicit publish.\n\nThis is consent before propagation. It is not a secrecy layer after publication:\nonce metadata has been synced to a remote, this feature should not pretend it can\nmake that data private again.\n\n## Current Shape\n\nRelevant `git-meta` change:\n\n- `[REDACTED:path]` commit `4c03a95` (`Use local prefix for unshared metadata`)\n- `git-meta-lib` now treats `local:` as a hard serialization exclusion.\n- The check happens before user filter rules, so even a rule like\n  `route local:** private` cannot serialize `local:` keys.\n- This applies to every target and to values/tombstones that pass through\n  serialization.\n\nRelevant `but-agentlog` shape:\n\n- Capture writes project-scoped GitMeta keys like:\n  - `gitbutler:agent-sessions`\n  - `gitbutler:agent-session:<session>:...`\n  - `gitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:<target-kind>:<target-hash>`\n- The hook path records the transcript and then spawns `but agentlog sync`.\n- `skim`, `show`, \n[TRUNCATED]\n\nDo not design a full privacy policy system here. `local:` is a publication guard,\nnot encryption, access control, or a guarantee that captured local data is\nappropriate to share.\n\nDo not overfit the storage design before implementation. The task is to preserve\nthe current public shape while adding a local-first staging step.\n\nDo not solve full-app visibility yet. For now, unpublished/published status can\nsurface in `skim`; wider GitButler UI affordances are future work.\n\nDo not migrate existing already-published agentlogs back to local. Leave existing\npublished data alone and apply local-first behavior to new captures.\n\n## Engineering Notes\n\nThe main upstream dependency is already in place: `git-meta-lib` can keep\n`local:` keys out of serialized refs.\n\nThe main `but-agentlog` change is behavioral:\n\n- write captured data under `local:` by default\n- teach local reads/publish discovery to look at local agentlog indexes\n- keep published reads compatible with the existing `gitbutler:agentlog-*` keys\n- make `agentlog sync` harmless for unpublished captures\n\nPublishing should not become an O(total metadata) operation if we can avoid it.\nIf moving `local:gitbutler:...` to `gitbutler:...` needs a bulk prefix-rename or\natomic set-and-remove primitive, fix that in `[REDACTED:path]` rather\nthan papering over it downstream.\n\nAgent Trail likely does not need changes if published keys keep the current\nshape. It should continue to consume only materialized public metadata from\n`refs/meta/main`.\n\nIf downstream behavior does need to change, the downstream scope should be\nlimited to `[REDACTED:path]`.\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Should `publish` move local data or copy it and leave a local copy behind? Move\n  still looks like the right default, but implementation may uncover a reason to\n  keep local copies.\n- What exact `gitbutler.*` config key should control per-repo share-by-default?\n- Does `git-meta-lib` need an atomic `MetaEdit::Remove` or prefix-move API before\n  this is pleasant and safe to implement?\n","tool_name":"exec_command","tool_kind":"exec","tool_input":null,"exit_code":0,"outcome":"succeeded","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-31T12:15:48.479Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}